<DOC><DOCNO> AP880712-0290 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-88 2134EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-LotusSoftware     07-12 0209</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Lotus Software,0218</SECOND><HEAD>Lotus Announces New Agenda Personal Management Software</HEAD><DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lotus Development Corp. on Tuesdayannounced the release of its Lotus Agenda software designed to helppeople manage personal information.   The company said the software allows users to organize personalminutiae such as ideas, notes, lists, messages, telephone numbers,addresses and schedules in a variety of categories.   Development of the software began about 10 months ago, but theidea belonged to Lotus founder Mitchell D. Kapor, who wouldscribble notes and stuff them in his shirt pocket, only to losethem.   Lotus said its development program included more than 150corporate and individual testers. Agenda is being credited ascreating a new category of applications software called personalinformation management.   The company said Agenda allows users to enter information ``onthe fly,'' assign it to different categories as desired and observeit from multiple perspectives.   Categories might include tasks, departments, people, issues.Lotus Agenda can be used to manage sales accounts, projects andcalendars, examine news clips or just keep a list, the company said.   Lotus Agenda is priced at $395 and is available immediately.   The software runs under DOS 2.0 or higher on IBM PC, XT, AT andPS-2 or compatible personal computers.</TEXT></DOC>